The denotational semantics is given in \cref{fig:den-sem1}. Points worth noting:
\begin{itemize}
\item We have one semantic function (here $\semfun{E}$ and $\semfun{V}$) for each syntactic
  non terminal (here $e$ and $v$ respectively.)
\item Each function has one equation for each form of the construct.
\item Both functions take an environment $\rho$ that maps in-scope identifiers to
  a \emph{single} value; see the definition $\Env = Ident \rightarrow \Value$.
\item The value function $\semfun{V}$ returns a \emph{single value} $\Value$ while
  the expression function $\semfun{E}$ returns a \emph{sequence of values} $\Value^{*}$.
  Sequences are defined in \cref{fig:sequences}.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{The equations}

The equations themselves, in \cref{fig:den-sem1}
are beautifully simple and compositional, as a denotational semantics should be.
The equations for $\semfun{V}$ should be self-explanatory, but those for $\semfun{E}$ are more interesting.
\begin{itemize}
\item Values $\semapp{E}{|v|}{\rho}$: compute the single value for |v|, and return a singleton sequence of results.
The auxiliary function $\munit$ is defined at the bottom of \cref{fig:den-sem1}.
\item Choice $\semapp{E}{|e_1 choice e_2|}{\rho}$: take the union of the sequences returned by |e_1| and |e_2| respectively.a
  Since we return a \emph{sequence}, not a set, this ``union'' (written $\munion$)
  is just sequence concatention (see
  the bottom of the Figure.
\item Unification $\semapp{E}{|e_1 choice e_2|}{\rho}$: take the \emph{intersection} of the
  sequences returned by |e_1| and |e_2| respectively. Again this ``intersection'' operator $\mintersect$
  is defined at the bottom of \cref{fig:den-sem1}. We give it an actual definition, using a sequence
  comprehension, which does a cartesian product. The equality is mathematical equality of functions;
  which we can't implement for functions, but it will do as a start.
\item Sequencing $\semapp{E}{|e_1 ; e_2|}{\rho}$. Again we use an auxiliary function $\msemi$ to combine
  the meanings of |e_1| and |e_2|. The function $\msemi$ (bottom of \cref{fig:den-sem1} again
  uses a sequence comprehension.  Again it does a cartesian product, but without the equality constraint of $\mintersect$.
\item Function application $\semapp{E}{|apply1N v_1 v_2|}{\rho}$ is easy, because $\semfun{V}$ returns a single value: just apply
  the meaning of the function to the meaning of the argument.
\item One and all are staightforward.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Functions}

How are functions handled?
Values include lambdas, so this semantics says that a lambda evaluates to a singleton
sequence, whose only element is a function value. But that function value has
type $\Value \rightarrow \Value ^{*}$; that is, it is a function that takes a single
value and returns a \emph{sequence} of values.  This is not TimLambda, but it's simple and well-understood.

\subsection{Existentials}

The big excitement is the treatment of |defKW|. We must extend $\rho$, but what should we bind |x| to?  (Compare the
equation for $\semapp{V}{|lam x e|}{}$, where we have a value $w$ to hand.)
Our answer is simple: \emph{try all possible values, and union the results}.
Of course we can't possibly implement it like this, but it makes a great specification.
For example |def x (x=3)| tries all possible values for |x|, but only one of them succeeds, namely |3|, so
the semantics is a singleton sequence $[3]$.

But there is a Big Problem with this approach.  Consider |def x (x= (4 choice 3))|.  The existential
enumerates all possible values of x \emph{in some arbitrary order}, and takes the union (i.e. concatention)
of the results from each of these bindings.  Suppose that |defKW| enumerates |3| before |4|; then
the semantics of this expression is the sequence $[3,4]$, and not $[4,3]$ as it should be.
And yet returning a sequence (not a set nor a bag) is a key design choice in Verse.  What can we do?

