\Value & = & \bot \domplus \mathbb{Z} \domplus \tuple{\Value} \domplus (\Value \rightarrow \LblValue^{*}) \domplus \mathrm{WRONG} \\
\LblValue & = & \Lbl^{*} \times \Value \\
\Lbl & = & \lblleft \domplus \lblright \\
\Env & = & Ident \rightarrow \Value
\end{array} \\
\text{where}\; \begin{array}[t]{l}
    \text{$\tuple{\Value}$ is a tuple of values} \\
    \text{$\Value^{*}$ is a (semantic) sequence (monad) of values.}
    \end{array}
\\
\\[3mm]
\text{\bf Labelled sequences $\LblValue^{*}$} \\
\begin{array}{rrcl}
\text{Unit} & \munit(w) & = & [ \, ([], w) \, ] \\
\text{Concatenation} &  s_1 \munion s_2 & = & \mcompr{(\lblleft \scons l,w)}{\mbind{(l,w)}{s_1}} \cup
                                             \mcompr{(\lblright \scons l, w)}{\mbind{(l,w)}{s_2}} \\
\text{Intersection} &  s_1 \mintersect s_2 & = & \mcompr{(l_1,w_1)}{\mbind{(l_1,w_1)}{s_1}, \mbind{(l_2,w_2)}{s_2}, w_1=w_2} \\
\text{Sequencing}   &  s_1 \msemi s_2 & = & \mcompr{(\lblsemi{l_1}{l_2}, w_2)}{\mbind{(l_1,w_1)}{s_1}, \mbind{(l_2,w_2)}{s_2}} \\
\text{One}  & \mone(s) & = & \shead (\msort( s)) \\
\text{All}  & \mall(s) & = & \stuple (\msort( s) ) \\
\\
\text{Sort} & \msort & : & \LblValue^{*} \rightarrow \Value^{*} \\
& \msort( s ) & = & \mcompr{w}{\mbind{([],w)}{s}} \\
  &&& \sconcat \msort \mcompr{(l,w)}{\mbind{(\lblleft:l,w)}{s}} \\
  &&& \sconcat \msort \mcompr{(l,w)}{\mbind{(\lblright:l,w)}{s}} \\
  \end{array}
\end{array}
$$
\caption{Labelled expression semantics}
\label{fig:den-sem2}
\end{figure}

\Cref{fig:den-sem2} give a new denotational semantics that \emph{does} account for order.
The key idea (due to Joachim) is this: return a sequence of \emph{labelled} values;
and then sort that sequence (in $\mone$ and $\mall$) into canonical order
before exposing it to the programmer.

We do not change the equations for $\semfun{E}$ and $\semfun{V}$ at all; they remain
precisely as they are in \Cref{fig:den-sem1}.  But we do change $\semfun{E}$'s type,
so that it retuns a sequence of \emph{labelled} values $\LblValue^{*}$.
A labelled value (of type $\LblValue$) is defined in \cref{fig:den-sem2},
and is just a pair of a \emph{label} of type $\Lbl^{*}$ and a value.
A label is a sequence of tags, where a tag is just $\lblleft$ or $\lblright$.

Now, the union (or concatention) operation $\munion$, defined in \cref{fig:den-sem2},
adds a $\lblleft$ tag to the labels of the values in the left branch of the choice,
and a $\lblright$ tag to those coming from the right.
So the labels specify where in the tree the value comes from.

Sequencing $\msemi$ concatenates the labels.
Notice that $\mintersect$ takes the labels entirely from the left argument.
(We need an example to explain this point.)

Finally $\msort$ puts everything in the ``right'' order: first the values with
an empty label, then the values whose label starts with $\lblleft$ (notice the
recursive sort of the trimmed-down sequence), and then those that start with $\lblright$.
Notice that $\msort$ removes all the labels, leaving just a bare sequence of values $\Value^{*}$.

Let us look at our troublesome example |def x (x= (4 choice 3))|, and assume that
|defKW| binds |x| to |3| and then |4|. The meaning of
this expression will be
$$
\semapp{E}{|def x (x= (4 choice 3))|}{\epsilon} \quad = \quad [ (\lblright,3), (\lblleft,4) ]
$$
Now if we take |allKW| of that expression we will get a singleton sequence
containing |tup (4,3)|, because |allKW| does a sort, stripping off all the tags.
$$
\semapp{E}{|all (def x (x= (4 choice 3)))|}{\epsilon} \quad = \quad [ ([], |tup (4,3)|) ]
$$

